[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] In mathematics and computer science, **connectivity** is one of the basic concepts of graph theory: it asks for the minimum number of elements (nodes or edges) that need to be removed to separate the remaining nodes into two or more isolated subgraphs.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] It is closely related to the theory of network flow problems.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] The connectivity of a graph is an important measure of its resilience as a network.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] In an undirected graph G, two vertices u and v are called **connected** if G contains a path from u to v.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] Otherwise, they are called **disconnected**.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] If the two vertices are additionally connected by a path of length 1 (that is, they are the endpoints of a single edge), the vertices are called **adjacent**.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] A graph is said to be **connected** if every pair of vertices in the graph is connected.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] This means that there is a path between every pair of vertices.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] An undirected graph that is not connected is called **disconnected**.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] An undirected graph G is therefore disconnected if there exist two vertices in G such that no path in G has these vertices as endpoints.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] A graph with just one vertex is connected.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] An edgeless graph with two or more vertices is disconnected.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] A directed graph is called **weakly connected** if replacing all of its directed edges with undirected edges produces a connected (undirected) graph.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] It is **unilaterally connected** or unilateral (also called **semiconnected**) if it contains a directed path from u to v or a directed path from v to u for every pair of vertices *u*, *v*.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] It is **strongly connected**, or simply strong, if it contains a directed path from u to v and a directed path from v to u for every pair of vertices *u*, *v*.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] A **connected component** is a maximal connected subgraph of an undirected graph.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] Each vertex belongs to exactly one connected component, as does each edge.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] A graph is connected if and only if it has exactly one connected component.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] The **strong components** are the maximal strongly connected subgraphs of a directed graph.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] A **vertex cut** or **separating set** of a connected graph G is a set of vertices whose removal renders G disconnected.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] The **vertex connectivity** *κ*(*G*) (where G is not a complete graph) is the size of a smallest vertex cut.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] A graph is called ***k*-vertex-connected** or ***k*-connected** if its vertex connectivity is k or greater.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] More precisely, any graph G (complete or not) is said to be *k-vertex-connected* if it contains at least *k* + 1 vertices, but does not contain a set of *k* − 1 vertices whose removal disconnects the graph; and *κ*(*G*) is defined as the largest k such that G is k-connected.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] In particular, a complete graph with n vertices, denoted Kn, has no vertex cuts at all, but *κ*(*Kn*) = *n* − 1.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] A **vertex cut** for two vertices u and v is a set of vertices whose removal from the graph disconnects u and v.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] The **local connectivity** *κ*(*u*, *v*) is the size of a smallest vertex cut separating u and v.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] Local connectivity is symmetric for undirected graphs; that is, *κ*(*u*, *v*) = *κ*(*v*, *u*).
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] Moreover, except for complete graphs, *κ*(*G*) equals the minimum of *κ*(*u*, *v*) over all nonadjacent pairs of vertices *u*, *v*.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] 2-connectivity is also called *biconnectivity* and 3-connectivity is also called *triconnectivity*.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] A graph G which is connected but not 2-connected is sometimes called *separable*.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] Analogous concepts can be defined for edges.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] In the simple case in which cutting a single, specific edge would disconnect the graph, that edge is called a *bridge*.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] More generally, an edge cut of G is a set of edges whose removal renders the graph disconnected.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] The *edge-connectivity* *λ*(*G*) is the size of a smallest edge cut, and the local edge-connectivity *λ*(*u*, *v*) of two vertices *u*, *v* is the size of a smallest edge cut disconnecting u from v.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] Again, local edge-connectivity is symmetric.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] A graph is called *k-edge-connected* if its edge connectivity is k or greater.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] A graph is said to be *maximally connected* if its connectivity equals its minimum degree.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] A graph is said to be *maximally edge-connected* if its edge-connectivity equals its minimum degree.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] A graph is said to be *super-connected* or *super-κ* if every minimum vertex cut isolates a vertex.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] A graph is said to be *hyper-connected* or *hyper-κ* if the deletion of each minimum vertex cut creates exactly two components, one of which is an isolated vertex.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] A graph is *semi-hyper-connected* or *semi-hyper-κ* if any minimum vertex cut separates the graph into exactly two components.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] More precisely: a G connected graph is said to be *super-connected* or *super-κ* if all minimum vertex-cuts consist of the vertices adjacent with one (minimum-degree) vertex.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] A G connected graph is said to be *super-edge-connected* or *super-λ* if all minimum edge-cuts consist of the edges incident on some (minimum-degree) vertex.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] A cutset X of G is called a non-trivial cutset if X does not contain the neighborhood N(*u*) of any vertex *u* ∉ *X*.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] A non-trivial edge-cut and the *edge-superconnectivity* $\lambda _{1}(G)$ are defined analogously.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] One of the most important facts about connectivity in graphs is Menger's theorem, which characterizes the connectivity and edge-connectivity of a graph in terms of the number of independent paths between vertices.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] If u and v are vertices of a graph G, then a collection of paths between u and v is called independent if no two of them share a vertex (other than u and v themselves).
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] Similarly, the collection is edge-independent if no two paths in it share an edge.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] The number of mutually independent paths between u and v is written as *κ*′(*u*, *v*), and the number of mutually edge-independent paths between u and v is written as *λ*′(*u*, *v*).
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] This fact is actually a special case of the max-flow min-cut theorem.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] The problem of determining whether two vertices in a graph are connected can be solved efficiently using a search algorithm, such as breadth-first search.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] More generally, it is easy to determine computationally whether a graph is connected (for example, by using a disjoint-set data structure), or to count the number of connected components.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] Proceed from that node using either depth-first or breadth-first search, counting all nodes reached.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] Once the graph has been entirely traversed, if the number of nodes counted is equal to the number of nodes of G, the graph is connected; otherwise it is disconnected.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] By Menger's theorem, for any two vertices u and v in a connected graph G, the numbers *κ*(*u*, *v*) and *λ*(*u*, *v*) can be determined efficiently using the max-flow min-cut algorithm.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] The connectivity and edge-connectivity of G can then be computed as the minimum values of *κ*(*u*, *v*) and *λ*(*u*, *v*), respectively.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] In computational complexity theory, SL is the class of problems log-space reducible to the problem of determining whether two vertices in a graph are connected, which was proved to be equal to L by Omer Reingold in 2004.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] Hence, undirected graph connectivity may be solved in O(log *n*) space.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] The problem of computing the probability that a Bernoulli random graph is connected is called network reliability and the problem of computing whether two given vertices are connected the ST-reliability problem.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/connectivity-graph-theory] The number of distinct connected labeled graphs with *n* nodes is tabulated in the On-Line Encyclopedia of Integer Sequences as sequence A001187.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] In graph theory, a **cut** is a partition of the vertices of a graph into two disjoint subsets.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] Any cut determines a **cut-set**, the set of edges that have one endpoint in each subset of the partition.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] These edges are said to **cross** the cut.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] In a connected graph, each cut-set determines a unique cut, and in some cases cuts are identified with their cut-sets rather than with their vertex partitions.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] In a flow network, an **s–t cut** is a cut that requires the *source* and the *sink* to be in different subsets, and its *cut-set* only consists of edges going from the source's side to the sink's side.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] The *capacity* of an s–t cut is defined as the sum of the capacity of each edge in the *cut-set*.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] A **cut** *C* = (*S*, *T*) is a partition of V of a graph *G* = (*V*, *E*) into two subsets S and T.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] The **cut-set** of a cut *C* = (*S*, *T*) is the set {(*u*, *v*) ∈ *E* | *u* ∈ *S*, *v* ∈ *T*} of edges that have one endpoint in S and the other endpoint in T.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] If s and t are specified vertices of the graph G, then an **s–t cut** is a cut in which s belongs to the set S and t belongs to the set T.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] In an unweighted undirected graph, the *size* or *weight* of a cut is the number of edges crossing the cut.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] In a weighted graph, the **value** or **weight** is defined by the sum of the weights of the edges crossing the cut.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] A **bond** is a cut-set that does not have any other cut-set as a proper subset.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] A cut is *minimum* if the size or weight of the cut is not larger than the size of any other cut.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] The illustration on the right shows a minimum cut: the size of this cut is 2, and there is no cut of size 1 because the graph is bridgeless.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] The max-flow min-cut theorem proves that the maximum network flow and the sum of the cut-edge weights of any minimum cut that separates the source and the sink are equal.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] There are polynomial-time methods to solve the min-cut problem, notably the Edmonds–Karp algorithm.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] A cut is *maximum* if the size of the cut is not smaller than the size of any other cut.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] The illustration on the right shows a maximum cut: the size of the cut is equal to 5, and there is no cut of size 6, or |*E*| (the number of edges), because the graph is not bipartite (there is an odd cycle).
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] In general, finding a maximum cut is computationally hard.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] The max-cut problem is one of Karp's 21 NP-complete problems.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] The max-cut problem is also APX-hard, meaning that there is no polynomial-time approximation scheme for it unless P = NP.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] However, it can be approximated to within a constant approximation ratio using semidefinite programming.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] Note that min-cut and max-cut are *not* dual problems in the linear programming sense, even though one gets from one problem to other by changing min to max in the objective function.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] The max-flow problem is the dual of the min-cut problem.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] The **sparsest cut problem** is to bipartition the vertices so as to minimize the ratio of the number of edges across the cut divided by the number of vertices in the smaller half of the partition.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] This objective function favors solutions that are both sparse (few edges crossing the cut) and balanced (close to a bisection).
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] The problem is known to be NP-hard, and the best known approximation algorithm is an $O({\sqrt {\log n}})$ approximation due to Arora, Rao & Vazirani (2009).
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] The family of all cut sets of an undirected graph is known as the **cut space** of the graph.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] It forms a vector space over the two-element finite field of arithmetic modulo two, with the symmetric difference of two cut sets as the vector addition operation, and is the orthogonal complement of the cycle space.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] If the edges of the graph are given positive weights, the minimum weight basis of the cut space can be described by a tree on the same vertex set as the graph, called the Gomory–Hu tree.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/cut-graph-theory] Each edge of this tree is associated with a bond in the original graph, and the minimum cut between two nodes *s* and *t* is the minimum weight bond among the ones associated with the path from *s* to *t* in the tree.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] In mathematics, a **graph partition** is the reduction of a graph to a smaller graph by partitioning its set of nodes into mutually exclusive groups.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Edges of the original graph that cross between the groups will produce edges in the partitioned graph.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] If the number of resulting edges is small compared to the original graph, then the partitioned graph may be better suited for analysis and problem-solving than the original.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Finding a partition that simplifies graph analysis is a hard problem, but one that has applications to scientific computing, VLSI circuit design, and task scheduling in multiprocessor computers, among others.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Recently, the graph partition problem has gained importance due to its application for clustering and detection of cliques in social, pathological and biological networks.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] For a survey on recent trends in computational methods and applications see Buluc et al.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Two common examples of graph partitioning are minimum cut and maximum cut problems.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Typically, graph partition problems fall under the category of NP-hard problems.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Solutions to these problems are generally derived using heuristics and approximation algorithms.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] However, uniform graph partitioning or a balanced graph partition problem can be shown to be NP-complete to approximate within any finite factor.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Even for special graph classes such as trees and grids, no reasonable approximation algorithms exist, unless P=NP.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Grids are a particularly interesting case since they model the graphs resulting from Finite Element Model (FEM) simulations.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] When not only the number of edges between the components is approximated, but also the sizes of the components, it can be shown that no reasonable fully polynomial algorithms exist for these graphs.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Consider a graph *G* = (*V*, *E*), where *V* denotes the set of *n* vertices and *E* the set of edges.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] For a (*k*,*v*) balanced partition problem, the objective is to partition *G* into *k* components of at most size *v* · (*n*/*k*), while minimizing the capacity of the edges between separate components.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Also, given *G* and an integer *k* > 1, partition *V* into *k* parts (subsets) *V*1, *V*2, ..., *Vk* such that the parts are disjoint and have equal size, and the number of edges with endpoints in different parts is minimized.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Such partition problems have been discussed in literature as bicriteria-approximation or resource augmentation approaches.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] A common extension is to hypergraphs, where an edge can connect more than two vertices.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] A hyperedge is not cut if all vertices are in one partition, and cut exactly once otherwise, no matter how many vertices are on each side.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] This usage is common in electronic design automation.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] For a specific (*k*, 1 + *ε*) balanced partition problem, we seek to find a minimum cost partition of *G* into *k* components with each component containing a maximum of (1 + *ε*)·(*n*/*k*) nodes.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] We compare the cost of this approximation algorithm to the cost of a (*k*,1) cut, wherein each of the *k* components must have the same size of (*n*/*k*) nodes each, thus being a more restricted problem.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] We already know that (2,1) cut is the minimum bisection problem and it is NP-complete.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Next, we assess a 3-partition problem wherein *n* = 3*k*, which is also bounded in polynomial time.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Now, if we assume that we have a finite approximation algorithm for (*k*, 1)-balanced partition, then, either the 3-partition instance can be solved using the balanced (*k*,1) partition in *G* or it cannot be solved.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] If the 3-partition instance can be solved, then (*k*, 1)-balanced partitioning problem in *G* can be solved without cutting any edge.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Otherwise, if the 3-partition instance cannot be solved, the optimum (*k*, 1)-balanced partitioning in *G* will cut at least one edge.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] An approximation algorithm with a finite approximation factor has to differentiate between these two cases.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Hence, it can solve the 3-partition problem which is a contradiction under the assumption that *P* = *NP*.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Thus, it is evident that (*k*,1)-balanced partitioning problem has no polynomial-time approximation algorithm with a finite approximation factor unless *P* = *NP*.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] The planar separator theorem states that any *n*-vertex planar graph can be partitioned into roughly equal parts by the removal of O(√*n*) vertices.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] This is not a partition in the sense described above, because the partition set consists of vertices rather than edges.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] However, the same result also implies that every planar graph of bounded degree has a balanced cut with O(√*n*) edges.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Since graph partitioning is a hard problem, practical solutions are based on heuristics.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] There are two broad categories of methods, local and global.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Well-known local methods are the Kernighan–Lin algorithm, and Fiduccia-Mattheyses algorithms, which were the first effective 2-way cuts by local search strategies.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Their major drawback is the arbitrary initial partitioning of the vertex set, which can affect the final solution quality.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Global approaches rely on properties of the entire graph and do not rely on an arbitrary initial partition.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] The most common example is spectral partitioning, where a partition is derived from approximate eigenvectors of the adjacency matrix, or spectral clustering that groups graph vertices using the eigendecomposition of the graph Laplacian matrix.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] A multi-level graph partitioning algorithm works by applying one or more stages.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Each stage reduces the size of the graph by collapsing vertices and edges, partitions the smaller graph, then maps back and refines this partition of the original graph.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] A wide variety of partitioning and refinement methods can be applied within the overall multi-level scheme.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] In many cases, this approach can give both fast execution times and very high quality results.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] One widely used example of such an approach is METIS, a graph partitioner, and hMETIS, the corresponding partitioner for hypergraphs.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] An alternative approach originated from and implemented, e.g., in scikit-learn is spectral clustering with the partitioning determined from eigenvectors of the graph Laplacian matrix for the original graph computed by LOBPCG solver with multigrid preconditioning.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Given a graph $G=(V,E)$ with adjacency matrix A , where an entry $A_{ij}$ implies an edge between node i and j , and degree matrix D , which is a diagonal matrix, where each diagonal entry of a row i , $d_{ii}$ , represents the node degree of node i .
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] The Laplacian matrix L is defined as $L=D-A$ .
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] of the number of edges that actually cross this cut to the number of pairs of vertices that could support such edges.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Spectral graph partitioning can be motivated by analogy with partitioning of a vibrating string or a mass-spring system and similarly extended to the case of negative weights of the graph.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] In such a scenario, the second smallest eigenvalue ( $\lambda _{2}$ ) of L , yields a *lower bound* on the optimal cost ( c ) of ratio-cut partition with $c\geq {\frac {\lambda _{2}}{n}}$ .
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] The eigenvector ( $V_{2}$ ) corresponding to $\lambda _{2}$ , called the *Fiedler vector*, bisects the graph into only two communities based on the ***sign** of the corresponding vector entry*.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Division into a larger number of communities can be achieved by repeated *bisection* or by using *multiple eigenvectors* corresponding to the smallest eigenvalues.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] The examples in Figures 1,2 illustrate the spectral bisection approach.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Minimum cut partitioning however fails when the number of communities to be partitioned, or the partition sizes are unknown.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] For instance, optimizing the cut size for free group sizes puts all vertices in the same community.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Additionally, cut size may be the wrong thing to minimize since a good division is not just one with small number of edges between communities.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] This motivated the use of Modularity (Q) as a metric to optimize a balanced graph partition.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] The example in Figure 3 illustrates 2 instances of the same graph such that in *(a)* modularity (Q) is the partitioning metric and in *(b)*, ratio-cut is the partitioning metric.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Another objective function used for graph partitioning is Conductance which is the ratio between the number of cut edges and the volume of the smallest part.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Conductance is related to electrical flows and random walks.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] The Cheeger bound guarantees that spectral bisection provides partitions with nearly optimal conductance.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] The quality of this approximation depends on the second smallest eigenvalue of the Laplacian λ2.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Graph partition can be useful for identifying the minimal set of nodes or links that should be immunized in order to stop epidemics.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Spin models have been used for clustering of multivariate data wherein similarities are translated into coupling strengths.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] The properties of ground state spin configuration can be directly interpreted as communities.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Thus, a graph is partitioned to minimize the Hamiltonian of the partitioned graph.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] The Hamiltonian (H) is derived by assigning the following partition rewards and penalties.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Additionally, Kernel-PCA-based Spectral clustering takes a form of least squares Support Vector Machine framework, and hence it becomes possible to project the data entries to a kernel induced feature space that has maximal variance, thus implying a high separation between the projected communities.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Some methods express graph partitioning as a multi-criteria optimization problem which can be solved using local methods expressed in a game theoretic framework where each node makes a decision on the partition it chooses.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] For very large-scale distributed graphs classical partition methods might not apply (e.g., spectral partitioning, Metis) since they require full access to graph data in order to perform global operations.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] For such large-scale scenarios distributed graph partitioning is used to perform partitioning through asynchronous local operations only.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] scikit-learn implements spectral clustering with the partitioning determined from eigenvectors of the graph Laplacian matrix for the original graph computed by ARPACK, or by LOBPCG solver with multigrid preconditioning.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] METIS is a graph partitioning family by Karypis and Kumar.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Among this family, kMetis aims at greater partitioning speed, hMetis, applies to hypergraphs and aims at partition quality, and ParMetis is a parallel implementation of the Metis graph partitioning algorithm.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] KaHyPar is a multilevel hypergraph partitioning framework providing direct k-way and recursive bisection based partitioning algorithms.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] It instantiates the multilevel approach in its most extreme version, removing only a single vertex in every level of the hierarchy.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] By using this very fine grained *n*-level approach combined with strong local search heuristics, it computes solutions of very high quality.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Scotch is graph partitioning framework by Pellegrini.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] It uses recursive multilevel bisection and includes sequential as well as parallel partitioning techniques.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Jostle is a sequential and parallel graph partitioning solver developed by Chris Walshaw.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] The commercialized version of this partitioner is known as NetWorks.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Party implements the Bubble/shape-optimized framework and the Helpful Sets algorithm.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] The software packages DibaP and its MPI-parallel variant PDibaP by Meyerhenke implement the Bubble framework using diffusion; DibaP also uses AMG-based techniques for coarsening and solving linear systems arising in the diffusive approach.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] Sanders and Schulz released a graph partitioning package KaHIP (Karlsruhe High Quality Partitioning) that implements for example flow-based methods, more-localized local searches and several parallel and sequential meta-heuristics.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/graph-partition] The tools Parkway by Trifunovic and Knottenbelt as well as Zoltan by Devine et al. focus on hypergraph partitioning.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] In a graph, a **maximum cut** is a cut whose size is at least the size of any other cut.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] That is, it is a partition of the graph's vertices into two complementary sets S and T, such that the number of edges between S and T is as large as possible.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] Finding such a cut is known as the **max-cut problem**.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] The problem can be stated simply as follows.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] One wants a subset S of the vertex set such that the number of edges between S and the complementary subset is as large as possible.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] Equivalently, one wants a bipartite subgraph of the graph with as many edges as possible.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] There is a more general version of the problem called **weighted max-cut**, where each edge is associated with a real number, its weight, and the objective is to maximize the total weight of the edges between S and its complement rather than the number of the edges.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] The weighted max-cut problem allowing both positive and negative weights can be trivially transformed into a weighted minimum cut problem by flipping the sign in all weights.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] The bound for connected graphs is often called the Edwards–Erdős bound as Erdős conjectured it.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] Edwards proved the Edwards-Erdős bound using the probabilistic method; Crowston et al. proved the bound using linear algebra and analysis of pseudo-boolean functions.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] The Edwards-Erdős bound extends to the **Balanced Subgraph Problem** (**BSP**) on signed graphs *G* = (*V*, *E*, *s*), i.e. graphs where each edge is assigned + or –.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] For a partition of V into subsets U and W, an edge xy is balanced if either *s*(*xy*) = + and x and y are in the same subset, or *s*(*xy*) = – and x and y are different subsets.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] BSP aims at finding a partition with the maximum number *b*(*G*) of balanced edges in G.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] The Edwards-Erdős gives a lower bound on *b*(*G*) for every connected signed graph G.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] Edwards's bound for arbitrary graphs was improved for special classes of graphs: triangle-free graphs, graphs of given maximum degree, H-free graphs, etc.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] Poljak and Turzik extended the Edwards-Erdős bound to weighted maximum cuts: the weight of a maximum cut is at least ${\frac {w(G)}{2}}+{\frac {w(T_{min})}{4}},$ where *w*(*G*) and *w*(*T*min) are the weights of G and its minimum weight spanning tree *T*min.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] Gutin and Yeo obtained a number of lower bounds for weighted Max-Cut extending the Poljak-Turzik bound for arbitrary weighted graphs and bounds for special classes of weighted graphs.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] This problem is known to be NP-complete.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] It is easy to see that the problem is in NP: a *yes* answer is easy to prove by presenting a large enough cut.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] The NP-completeness of the problem can be shown, for example, by a reduction from maximum 2-satisfiability (a restriction of the maximum satisfiability problem).
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] The weighted version of the decision problem was one of Karp's 21 NP-complete problems; Karp showed the NP-completeness by a reduction from the partition problem.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] The optimization variant is known to be NP-Hard.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] The opposite problem, that of finding a minimum cut is known to be efficiently solvable via the Ford–Fulkerson algorithm.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] As the maximum cut problem is NP-hard, no polynomial-time algorithms for Max-Cut in general graphs are known.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] The route inspection problem may be solved in polynomial time, and this duality allows the maximum cut problem to also be solved in polynomial time for planar graphs.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] The Maximum-Bisection problem is known however to be NP-hard.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] More generally, whenever maximum cuts can be found in polynomial time for certain classes of graphs, the algorithms for this problem can be extended to the 2- and 3-clique-sums of graphs in these classes.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] This allows the planar graph algorithm to be extended to certain broader families of graphs closed under graph minors and having the structure of clique-sums of planar graphs and graphs of bounded size.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] A minor-closed family of graphs has this clique-sum structure exactly when its forbidden minors include a graph with crossing number at most one.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] The Max-Cut Problem is APX-hard, meaning that there is no polynomial-time approximation scheme (PTAS), arbitrarily close to the optimal solution, for it, unless P = NP.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] Thus, every known polynomial-time approximation algorithm achieves an approximation ratio strictly less than one.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] There is a simple randomized 0.5-approximation algorithm: for each vertex flip a coin to decide to which half of the partition to assign it.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] In expectation, half of the edges are cut edges.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] This algorithm can be derandomized with the method of conditional probabilities; therefore there is a simple deterministic polynomial-time 0.5-approximation algorithm as well.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] One such algorithm starts with an arbitrary partition of the vertices of the given graph $G=(V,E)$ and repeatedly moves one vertex at a time from one side of the partition to the other, improving the solution at each step, until no more improvements of this type can be made.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] The number of iterations is at most $|E|$ because the algorithm improves the cut by at least one edge at each step.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] When the algorithm terminates, at least half of the edges incident to every vertex belong to the cut, for otherwise moving the vertex would improve the cut.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] Therefore, the cut includes at least $|E|/2$ edges.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] The polynomial-time approximation algorithm for Max-Cut with the best known approximation ratio is a method by Goemans and Williamson using a semidefinite program (which can be derived from the first level of the sum of squares hierarchy) and randomized rounding.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] If the unique games conjecture is true, this is the best possible approximation ratio for maximum cut.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] Without such unproven assumptions, it has been proven to be NP-hard to approximate the max-cut value with an approximation ratio better than ${\tfrac {16}{17}}\approx 0.941$ .
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] Dunning et al. provide an extended analysis of 10 heuristics for this problem, including open-source implementation.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] Crowston et al. proved that the problem can be solved in time $8^{k}O(n^{4})$ and admits a kernel of size $O(k^{5})$ .
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] They also extended the fixed-parameter tractability result to the Balanced Subgraph Problem (BSP, see Lower bounds above) and improved the kernel size to $O(k^{3})$ (holds also for BSP).
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] Etscheid and Mnich improved the fixed-parameter tractability result for BSP to $8^{k}O(m)$ and the kernel-size result to $O(k)$ vertices.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] Weighted maximum cuts can be found in polynomial time in graphs of bounded treewidth.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] That is, when parameterized by treewidth rather than by the cut size, the weighted maximum cut problem is fixed-parameter tractable.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] It remains fixed-parameter tractable for sm-width, another graph width parameter intermediate between treewidth and clique-width.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] However, under standard assumptions in parameterized complexity, it is not fixed-parameter tractable for clique-width.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] Treating its nodes as features and its edges as distances, the max cut algorithm divides a graph in two well-separated subsets.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] In other words, it can be naturally applied to perform binary classification.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] Compared to more common classification algorithms, it does not require a feature space, only the distances between elements within.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] In statistical physics and disordered systems, the Max Cut problem is equivalent to minimizing the Hamiltonian of a spin glass model, most simply the Ising model.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] Here each vertex *i* of the graph is a spin site that can take a spin value $s_{i}=\pm 1.$ A spin configuration partitions $V(G)$ into two sets, those with spin up $V^{+}$ and those with spin down $V^{-}.$ We denote with $\delta (V^{+})$ the set of edges that connect the two sets.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] Minimizing this energy is equivalent to the min-cut problem or by setting the graph weights as $w_{ij}=-J_{ij},$ the max-cut problem.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/maximum-cut] The max cut problem has applications in VLSI design.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/minimum-cut] In graph theory, a **minimum cut** or **min-cut** of a graph is a cut (a partition of the vertices of a graph into two disjoint subsets) that is minimal in some metric.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/minimum-cut] In the simplest *unweighted min-cut problem*, the goal is to minimize the number of edges connecting the two parts.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/minimum-cut] Variations of the minimum cut problem consider *weighted graphs*, *directed graphs*, *terminals*, and partitioning the vertices into *more than two sets*.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/minimum-cut] The weighted min-cut problem allowing both positive and negative weights can be trivially transformed into a weighted maximum cut problem by flipping the sign in all weights.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/minimum-cut] The required output is a partition V = S + T (a partition of the vertices into two disjoint subsets S and T).
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/minimum-cut] Any such partition has a *cost,* and the goal is to find a partition with a smallest cost.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/minimum-cut] A generalization of the minimum cut problem without terminals is the minimum k-cut, in which the goal is to partition the graph into at least k connected components by removing as few edges as possible.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/minimum-cut] For a fixed value of k, this problem can be solved in polynomial time, though the algorithm is not practical for large k.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/minimum-cut] In the variant called *min s-t cut*, the input contains, in addition to the graph, two nodes called *s* (source) and *t* (target / sink).
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/minimum-cut] The required output is a partition V = S + T such that s is in S and t is in T.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/minimum-cut] In a flow network, the minimum cut separates the source and sink vertices and minimizes the total sum of the capacities of the edges that are directed from the source side of the cut to the sink side of the cut.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/minimum-cut] As shown in the max-flow min-cut theorem, the weight of this cut equals the maximum amount of flow that can be sent from the source to the sink in the given network.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/minimum-cut] In a weighted, undirected network, it is possible to calculate the cut that separates a particular pair of vertices from each other and has minimum possible total cost.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/minimum-cut] A system of cuts that solves this problem for every possible vertex pair can be collected into a structure known as the Gomory–Hu tree of the graph.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/minimum-cut] A generalization of the minimum cut problem with terminals is the k-terminal cut, or multi-terminal cut.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/minimum-cut] In a planar graph, this problem can be solved in polynomial time.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/minimum-cut] However, in general this problem is NP-hard, even for $k=3$ .
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/minimum-cut] Graph partition problems are a family of combinatorial optimization problems in which a graph is to be partitioned into two or more parts with additional constraints such as balancing the sizes of the two sides of the cut.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/minimum-cut] Segmentation-based object categorization can be viewed as a specific case of normalized min-cut spectral clustering applied to image segmentation.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/minimum-cut] It can also be used as a generic clustering method, where the nodes are data samples assumed to be taken from a metric space and edge weights are their distances.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/minimum-cut] This is however often impractical due do the high computational complexity for $k>2$ .
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/minimum-cut] Due to max-flow min-cut theorem, 2 nodes' Minimum cut value is equal to their maxflow value.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/minimum-cut] In this case, some algorithms used in maxflow problem could also be used to solve this question.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/minimum-cut] A graph with n vertices can at the most have ${\binom {n}{2}}={\frac {n(n-1)}{2}}$ distinct minimum cuts.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/minimum-cut] This bound is tight in the sense that a (simple) cycle on n vertices has exactly ${\frac {n(n-1)}{2}}$ minimum cuts.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] In graph theory, the **Stoer–Wagner algorithm** is a recursive algorithm to solve the minimum cut problem in undirected weighted graphs with non-negative weights.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] It was proposed by Mechthild Stoer and Frank Wagner in 1995.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] The essential idea of this algorithm is to shrink the graph by merging the most intensive vertices, until the graph only contains two combined vertex sets.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] At each phase, the algorithm finds the minimum s - t cut for two vertices s and t chosen at its will.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] Then the algorithm shrinks the edge between s and t to search for non s - t cuts.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] The minimum cut found in all phases will be the minimum weighted cut of the graph.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] A **cut** is a partition of the vertices of a graph into two non-empty, disjoint subsets.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] A minimum cut is a cut for which the size or weight of the cut is not larger than the size of any other cut.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] For an unweighted graph, the minimum cut would simply be the cut with the least edges.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] For a weighted graph, the sum of all edges' weight on the cut determines whether it is a minimum cut.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] In practice, the minimum cut problem is always discussed with the maximum flow problem, to explore the maximum capacity of a network, since the minimum cut is a bottleneck in a graph or network.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] Let $G=(V,E,w)$ be a weighted undirected graph.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] The cut is called an s - t cut if exactly one of s or t is in S .
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] The minimal cut of G that is also an s - t cut is called the s - t min-cut of G .
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] This algorithm starts by finding an s and a t in V , and an s-t min-cut $(S,T)$ of G .
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] For any pair $\left\{s,t\right\}$ , there are two possible situations: either $(S,T)$ is a global min-cut of G , or s and t belong to the same side of the global min-cut of G .
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] Therefore, the global min-cut can be found by checking the graph $G\cup \{st\}/\left\{s,t\right\}$ , which is the graph after merging vertices s and t into a new vertex $st$ .
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] During the merging, if s and t are connected by an edge then this edge disappears.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] If s and t both have edges to some vertex v , then the weight of the edge from the new vertex $st$ to v is $w(s,v)+w(t,v)$ .
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] In the MinimumCutPhase, the subset A of the graphs vertices grows starting with an arbitrary single vertex until A is equal to V .
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] In each step, the vertex which is outside of A , but most tightly connected with A is added to the set A .
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] This procedure can be formally shown as: add vertex $z\notin A$ such that $w(A,z)=\max\{w(A,y)\mid y\notin A\}$ , where $w(A,y)$ is the sum of the weights of all the edges between A and y .
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] So, in a single phase, a pair of vertices s and t , and a min $s{\text{-}}t$ cut C is determined.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] After one phase of the MinimumCutPhase, the two vertices are merged as a new vertex, and edges from the two vertices to a remaining vertex are replaced by an edge weighted by the sum of the weights of the previous two edges.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] Edges joining the merged nodes are removed.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] If there is a minimum cut of G separating s and t , the C is a minimum cut of G .
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] If not, then the minimum cut of G must have s and t on a same side.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] Therefore, the algorithm would merge them as one node.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] In addition, the MinimumCut would record and update the global minimum cut after each MinimumCutPhase.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] After $n-1$ phases, the minimum cut can be determined.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] The graph in step 1 shows the original graph G and randomly selects node 2 as the starting node for this algorithm.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] In the MinimumCutPhase, set A only has node 2, the heaviest edge is edge (2,3), so node 3 is added into set A .
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] Next, set A contains node 2 and node 3, the heaviest edge is (3,4), thus node 4 is added to set A .
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] By following this procedure, the last two nodes are node 5 and node 1, which are s and t in this phase.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] By merging them into node 1+5, the new graph is as shown in step 2.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] In this phase, the weight of cut is 5, which is the summation of edges (1,2) and (1,5).
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] Right now, the first loop of MinimumCut is completed.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] In step 2, starting from node 2, the heaviest edge is (2,1+5), thus node 1+5 is put in set A .
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] The next heaviest edges is (2,3) or (1+5,6), we choose (1+5,6) thus node 6 is added to the set.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] Then we compare edge (2,3) and (6,7) and choose node 3 to put in set A .
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] The last two nodes are node 7 and node 8.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] The minimum cut is 5, so remain the minimum as 5.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] The following steps repeat the same operations on the merged graph, until there is only one edge in the graph, as shown in step 7.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] The global minimum cut has edge (2,3) and edge (6,7), which is detected in step 5.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] To prove the correctness of this algorithm, we need to prove that the cut given by MinimumCutPhase is in fact a minimum $s{\text{-}}t$ cut of the graph, where s and t are the two vertices last added in the phase.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] Let $C=(X,{\overline {X}})$ be an arbitrary $s{\text{-}}t$ cut, and $CP$ be the cut given by the phase.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] Observe that a single run of MinimumCutPhase gives us an ordering of all the vertices in the graph (where a is the first and s and t are the two vertices added last in the phase).
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] We say the vertex v is active if v and the vertex added just before v are in opposite sides of the cut.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] We prove the lemma by induction on the set of active vertices.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] We define $A_{v}$ as the set of vertices added to A before v , and $C_{v}$ to be the set of edges in C with both of their ends in $A_{v}\cup \{v\}$ , i.e. $C_{v}\subseteq C$ is the cut induced by $A_{v}\cup \{v\}$ .
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] By the definition of these two quantities, $w(A_{v_{0}},v_{0})$ and $w(C_{v_{0}})$ are equivalent. $A_{v_{0}}$ is simply all vertices added to A before $v_{0}$ , and the edges between these vertices and $v_{0}$ are the edges that cross the cut C .
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] Therefore, the cut of the phase is at most as heavy as C .
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] The running time of the algorithm **MinimumCut** is equal to the added running time of the $|V|-1$ runs of **MinimumCutPhase**, which is called on graphs with decreasing number of vertices and edges.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] For the **MinimumCutPhase**, a single run of it needs at most $O(|E|+|V|\log |V|)$ time.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] Therefore, the overall running time should be the product of two phase complexity, which is $O(|V||E|+|V|^{2}\log |V|)$ .
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] For the further improvement, the key is to make it easy to select the next vertex to be added to the set A , the most tightly connected vertex.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] During execution of a phase, all vertices that are not in A reside in a priority queue based on a key field.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] The key of a vertex V is the sum of the weights of the edges connecting it to the current A , that is, $w(A,v)$ .
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] Whenever a vertex v is added to A we have to perform an update of the queue. v has to be deleted from the queue, and the key of every vertex w not in A , connected to v has to be increased by the weight of the edge $vw$ , if it exists.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] As this is done exactly once for every edge, overall we have to perform $|V|$ ExtractMax and $|E|$ IncreaseKey operations.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] By using the Fibonacci heap we can perform an ExtractMax operation in $O(\log |V|)$ amortized time and an IncreaseKey operation in $O(1)$ amortized time.
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] Thus, the time we need for this key step that dominates the rest of the phase, is $O(|E|+|V|\log |V|)$ .
[src:stoer-wagner-mincut/stoer-wagner-algorithm] Below is a concise C++ implementation of the Stoer–Wagner algorithm.
